Title: uclasc_94_001_01_001
Description.note: Typed description of following photo: No.1. The concrete-steel headgates of the Imperial Canal at Hanlons, Cal. Completed June 29, 1906, by C. Leonardt, Con-tractor, on plans designed by J.D. Schuyler, drawn by Geo. S. Binckley. Taken July 16, 1906. View from the shore end, looking toward the Colorado river, 1200 feet distant.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_002
Description.note: Typed description: Snapshot views of concrete-steel radial headgates, at Henlons, Cal. et head of Imperial Canal, and of the 200-ft. wooden gate at the Lower Mexican Intake, taken by J.D. Schuyler, July 16, 1906.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_004
Description.note: Typed description of uclasc_94_001_003: No. 2. The headgates, from the river side of the canal looking toward the natural granite abutment, on the up-stream side,- showing the shutter-gates in navigation pass raised.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_005
Description.note: Photo of canal headgates.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_006
Description.note: Typed Description of photograph: No. 3. The radial gates from the lower side, looking southeast towards the river. The gates are shown partially raised. The water here shown is over 10 feet deep over the floor of the gates.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_007
Description.note: Photograph of canal from opposite side.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_008
Description.note: Typed description of previous photograph on back of photograph: No. 4. There are 11 of these gates, each 12 ft. wide, 10 feet high, besides the navigation pass. A velocity of but 7 ft. per second is required to give a discharge of 10,000 sec-ft. enough water to irrigate one million acres. A difference in head of 1 foot on upper side above that on the lower will give this velocity.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_009
Description.note: Photo of canal

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_010
Description.note: Typed description of next photo: No. 5. View through the navigation pass. This is intended only for the gasoline launch of the Co. The party in the group, from right to left are: H.T. Cory, Gen. Mgr. Cal. Dev. Co., Standing alone; Col.R. H. Ingram, Gen. Supt. S.P..R.R., with Carrillo behind; next Prof Hughes, next?. then Col. Henver, USA Corps of Engineers; Mr. A. H. Heber; Mr. A. d'Heur and Mr. L.W. Long, the two latter of the Engr. Corps Son. Pso. R.R.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_011
Description.note: Canal opening

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_012
Description.note: Typed description for following photos: No. 6. Looking along the top of the gate, showing the hoisting gear and connection for gasoline engine to actuate the shaft which is to be added later. Two men can raise a gate, but with the engine but one attendant will be required.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_013
Description.note: Photograph taken from on top of the canal.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_014
Description.note: Typed description of following photograph: No. 7. A rear view of one of the hoisting drums, with phosphor bronze cable, bevel gear and worm gear, controlling lever, etc.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_015
Description.note: Photograph of group of men on top of canal.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_016
Description.note: Typed description of photograph 8: No. 8. A general view of the 200-ft. wooden gate, at the lower Mexican Intake, through which the river is to be diverted while the break is being closed with a dam. Looking up the original Imperial Canal... Taken July 16, '06.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_017
Description.note: Distant photograph of canal.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_018
Description.note: Description of file 019: No. 2. Front view of the 500-ft. gate, looking down stream. There are about 13 feet of water over the floor of this gate as shown here.

Title: ucalsc_94_001_01_020
Description.note: Description of 021: No. 10. The 200-ft. gate from the upper side. Only one-half the full height of this gate is here shown above the water. With free waterway above and below a head of 2-1/4 force 20,000 sec-ft. through this structure.

Title: uclasc_94_001_01_022
Description.note: Description of 023: No. 11. View of the 200-ft. wooden gate, showing the end toward the river, which will be joined to the fame to be built across the break.
